#14200
@@bTidemouth Trail, Western Edge@@N~
@@bThe Saltglass Reach ends here in a long exhale of salt crust and wind-scoured gravel, the last coherent surface before the dunes begin their slow dissolution into shoreline chaos.@@N The pale ground carries the ghost of a road — two parallel furrows worn by countless caravan wheels — but the furrows fade within a hundred paces eastward into a braided mess of dune crossings and tidal channels. @@lA smell of brine arrives from the east in irregular pulses, stronger when the wind turns off the sea, cutting through the dusty Reach air like a blade slipped between ledger pages.@@N To the west, the Saltglass corridor continues its long reach toward the interior, its route-marker cairns visible for a short distance before heat shimmer consumes them. @@yA Survey-Administrative inscription carved into a flat stone at the trail's edge reads: TIDEMOUTH BOUNDARY — SHOREWARD CONVERSION REQUIRED — PRESENT TRANSIT SEAL AT LANDWARD GATE.@@N Every caravan that has passed here has left some residue: broken wheel spokes, emptied waterskins, a discarded sandal sole, the ash ring of a cooking fire.
