@@bBrackish Channel Crossing@@N~
@@lA shallow brackish channel cuts across the tidal flat here, wide enough to require several careful steps through ankle-deep water that carries a bitter mineral taste.@@N The channel bottom is packed sand and broken shell, stable enough to cross but treacherous for draft animals and loaded wagon wheels, which explains the remains of an improvised plank bridge — now half-collapsed — that a previous caravan group left in place. @@bThe water is the colour of old brass, stained by the @@ldissolved Saltglass minerals carried down from the Reach.@@N @@bOn the far bank, @@bcrab burrow holes@@N are denser, their entrances freshly turned in the moist soil.@@N The sound of water moving against the channel banks is faint but continuous, driven by tidal pressure even this far inland.
