@@bThe old assessment hall is a substantial ruin — thick stone walls still standing to full height on three sides, the fourth collapsed inward across a floor buried in accumulated dune sand.@@N The building predates the current gate structure by at least two generations; its architectural style uses the wider basalt blocks of an earlier quarrying tradition. @@yColumn niches along the inner walls once held standing bronze balance arms for cargo weighing; the niches are empty now, but the anchor bolt holes are still visible and cut to a precision that speaks to the serious commercial purpose this building once served.@@N The transition of the assessment function to the gate customs yard made this building redundant, and it has been abandoned to slow collapse.
