#14224
@@yThe Landward Gate of Mafdet@@N~
@@yThe gate arch is built in the same dark basalt as the wall, but wider and more deeply carved — every surface carries some notation, from the founding charter text inscribed across the lintel in the Survey-Administrative register to the Measure Script harbor-authority seal cut into the keystone.@@N The iron-reinforced doors are massive, each requiring a team of four to swing, and they are held open by chain catches set into the cobble during daylight hours. A signal lantern in a housing above the arch burns day and night, its light calibrated to be visible from the signal tower in the harbor. @@yGate guards occupy posts to either side of the arch, their posture suggesting long practice rather than immediate alert — this is a routine inspection post, not a military position.@@N The air here is a sharply defined boundary of its own: west of the arch, the Reach's dust and mineral smell; east, the city's composite of salt, tar, animal dung, and cooked food. @@lFrom the gate, the view east opens into the lower Carter's Way with its constant caravan traffic and the distant glint of harbor water.@@N The gate represents the full weight of the Shoreward Compact's jurisdictional transition — every obligation, right, and legal standing carried by an incoming caravan is formally reinterpreted here.
